  "text": "Hypertrophic and, thus, undesired late aspects of chondrogenesis like ALP enzyme activity were most pronounced in pellet cultures followed by collagen gel. Consistent with the role of ALP in matrix calcification, these composites underwent the strongest calcification in vivo together with fibrin which, however, had a lower ALP enzyme activity in vitro. PuraMatrix constructs consistently did not display any ALP activity in vitro although calcification of constructs was observed with some donor cells. Together this demostrated that ALP enzyme activity detected in vitro, was no secure means to predict the extent of in vivo calcification. Since constructs are in vivo no longer under the influence of medium components like TGF-beta, a known suppressor of chondrocyte maturation and calcification [CITATION_1] , ALP activity may have developed differently during the 4 weeks in vivo period. Matrigel as a complex biomaterial contains growth factors including small amounts of TGF-beta and is mainly composed of collagen type IV, a matrix molecule with TGF-beta binding capacity [CITATION_2] . It may further contain a variety of factors capable to suppress in vivo calcification. Thus, the complex composition of Matrigel and a potential TGF-beta storage capacity during culture may have mediated its enhanced capability to endure stabilization of ectopic transplants in the absence of calcification. At optimal conditions, four of four donor cell populations displayed a deposition of cartilaginous matrix in all carrier materials (A-E), while at suboptimal conditions carrier-free pellets were always negative (F, K). At suboptimal conditions, two of four cell populations showed a deposition of cartilaginous matrix in all carrier-materials (G-J), but two other donor cell populations only deposited detectable amounts of cartilaginous matrix in PuraMatrix (O).",
